{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/sinusitis/background-information/causes/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"d0ca7ab5-8889-52dd-8ac6-bcf949adf403","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field db193de6-4bf0-469e-8429-e9844951bbfa --><h2>What causes it?</h2><!-- end field db193de6-4bf0-469e-8429-e9844951bbfa -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 05a8e7e9-060d-414d-8746-e1da1def24c8 --><!-- begin field 2b50f74c-d5e3-4ab2-a34b-e33f95fc86e1 --><ul><li><strong>Acute sinusitis</strong> is usually triggered by a viral upper respiratory tract infection (for example, rhinovirus, respiratory syncytial virus, parainfluenza, or influenza) which can be followed by bacterial infection [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Foden et al, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Rosenfeld et al, 2015</a>]. <ul><li>Sinus mucosa oedema, obstruction of the sinus ostia, and reduction in mucociliary action allow secretions to stagnate and give bacteria a suitable environment in which to grow [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Aring and Chan, 2016</a>]. Although it is estimated that only 0.5–2.0% of people will subsequently develop a bacterial infection [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Gwaltney, 1996</a>], the most commonly implicated bacteria are <em>Streptococcus pneumoniae </em>and <em>Haemophilus influenzae</em>, <em>Moraxella catarrhalis, and Staphylococcus aureus </em>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Foden et al, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Rosenfeld, 2016</a>].  </li><li>Acute sinusitis is also associated with [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Foden et al, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Aring and Chan, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Rosenfeld, 2016</a>]:<ul><li>Asthma.</li><li>Allergic rhinitis.</li><li>Smoking.</li><li>Anatomical variation or mechanical obstruction (for example, deviated nasal septum, nasal polyps, trauma, foreign body).</li><li>Seasonal variation (more likely to occur in the early months of the year).</li><li>Impaired ciliary motility (for example, cystic fibrosis).</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Chronic sinusitis</strong> is more likely to be inflammatory than an infectious process [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Sedaghat, 2017</a>], but its<strong> </strong>aetiology is likely to be multifactorial, for example, involving inflammation, infection, and obstruction of sinus ventilation [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">ENT UK and Royal College of Surgeons, 2016</a>]. In chronic sinusitis, different bacteria predominate compared with acute bacterial sinusitis (<em>Staphylococcus aureus</em>, Enterobacteriaceae spp, and Pseudomonas), but their role is uncertain [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Kaplan, 2013</a>]. <ul><li>Possible predisposing factors and associated conditions include [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sinusitis/references/\">Fokkens et al, 2012</a>]: <ul><li><strong>Atopy</strong> (allergic rhinitis) — it is thought that swollen nasal mucosa at the site of the sinus ostia may compromise ventilation or obstruct the ostia, leading to mucus retention and infection.</li><li><strong>Asthma</strong> — frequently associated with chronic sinusitis with nasal polyps but the relationship is poorly understood.</li><li><strong>Ciliary impairment</strong> — inability of the cilia to transport mucus from the sinuses is thought to be a cause of chronic sinusitis in conditions such as cystic fibrosis. </li><li><strong>Aspirin sensitivity</strong> — there is an association between aspirin sensitivity and chronic sinusitis with nasal polyps.</li><li><strong>Immunocompromise</strong> — dysfunction of the immune system can be associated with chronic sinusitis.</li><li><strong>Genetic factors</strong> — chronic sinusitis without nasal polyps can run in families although no genetic abnormality linked to chronic sinusitis has been identified.</li><li><strong>Cigarette smoking</strong> — chronic sinusitis is more common in people who smoke.</li><li><strong>Iatrogenic factors</strong> — sinus surgery can result in an increased risk of persistent sinus infection.</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 2b50f74c-d5e3-4ab2-a34b-e33f95fc86e1 --><!-- end item 05a8e7e9-060d-414d-8746-e1da1def24c8 -->","topic":{"id":"6d2333af-675d-5bf3-8f7d-21404b5f0aa9","topicId":"251eec02-9620-4893-97bb-7a4e69e81da3","topicName":"Sinusitis","slug":"sinusitis","lastRevised":"Last revised in June 2018","chapters":[{"id":"2e4afda1-e9d5-5296-a027-01f4617ab6d0","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"405b3d6d-e395-5fea-bc5e-02ddf80a8bd2","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"22d307e8-3756-562c-b49a-55d20a9d0c5d","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"36290f8d-5730-5655-8fa4-0d3f584a2980","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"b0ba5cc8-0ed6-52d6-86c5-12833f47d8d3","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"f730377b-2158-527d-b9a1-e99c0653afd0","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","